## 2. Architecture Overview

    TARGET (38.34.110.236)
      └─ outbound SSH (TCP 443)
           → SOURCE (95.165.84.3)
                └─ reverse tunnel: localhost:13389 → TARGET:3389
  TARGET (69.140.56.80)
      └─ outbound SSH (TCP 443)
           → SOURCE (95.165.84.3)
                └─ reverse tunnel: localhost:13390 → TARGET:3389

*   Port **13389 amd 13390** exists only on SOURCE and only on `localhost`
*   No RDP ports are exposed to the internet
*   Tunnel is encrypted and key‑based

***
Install OpenSSH

On SOURCE (server)
Add-WindowsCapability -Online -Name OpenSSH.Server~~~~0.0.1.0

Start-Service sshd
Set-Service sshd -StartupType Automatic

On TARGET (client)
Add-WindowsCapability -Online -Name OpenSSH.Client~~~~0.0.1.0

Configure
Lock down SSH on SOURCE (critical)
Edit as Administrator:
C:\ProgramData\ssh\sshd_config

Ensure these settings:
Port 443
AllowTcpForwarding yes
GatewayPorts no
PasswordAuthentication yes
PubkeyAuthentication no
PermitTunnel no

Restart SSH:
Restart-Service sshd

Router config (SOURCE location)
Port‑forward one port only:
TCP 443 → SOURCE internal IP

(If your ISP blocks 22, change SSH to 443 and forward that instead.)


Test Source
